A week later, a certified letter came from a lawyer in Nebraska. My parents farm was $340,000 in debt. Equipment loans, bad harvests, medical bills from Dad's back surgery. The bank was foreclosing in 30 days. The letter ended with my father's cell number. I stared at that number for hours before calling. His voice sounded older. Smaller somehow. Son, he said. Like he'd never thrown me away. We made mistakes. We met at a steakhouse near their farm. Mom hugged me too tight. Dad's hands had new calluses, his face more lines. voice_to_text: Who was secretly exhausting your teenager every weekend. My 14 year old daughter started asking to sleep over at friends houses every weekend. And I thought it was just normal teenage social stuff. But then I noticed the pattern. Every Monday morning she'd come home looking absolutely destroyed. Dark circles so deep they looked like bruises. Shoulders hunched, dragging her feet like each step hurt. When I asked about the sleepovers, he just mumbled it was fun and disappear into her room. Her math teacher emailed saying she had a panic attack during class when he'd casually asked about her weekend plans. Her violent teacher called to say she quit, just walked out mid lesson without explanation. She lost 10 pounds in just over a month. Her favorite jeans hung loose on her hips. She barely touched breakfast anymore. Started missing Sunday family dinners, events she'd never miss before, not even when she had the flu. My partner thought I was losing it. She's 14, Lisa. Girls have sleepovers. You're being paranoid. But when I was cleaning her room, I found energy drink cans stuffed behind her dresser, dozens of them. My sweet girl who used to drink nothing but herbal tea, my mom instincts weren't just whispering anymore, they were screaming. I started watching her more carefully. She'd get texts on Friday afternoon and her whole body would change. Shoulders would tense up, face would go pale, hands would start trembling as she packed always the same overnight bag. But I noticed something odd. Work gloves sticking out of the side pocket. No more family game nights on Saturdays. No more baking cookies together on Sunday mornings. No more asking me to braid her hair before bed. It was like she was being pulled away from us by some invisible force. One day I was passing her room when I heard her on the phone. Her voice was different, scared, desperate almost. I know, I know. I'll be there, her voice cracked. I can't do this every weekend anymore. Please pause. No, I understand. I promise I won't tell anyone. Then I heard her crying, real gut wrenching sobs that made my chest tighten. The next morning at breakfast, I asked casually, which friend's house are you going to tonight, honey? Her spoon clattered into her cereal bowl. Her eyes darted to her phone like it might save her. Just, just Marlene's. Her mom already said yes. But I called Marlene's mom last week. Marlene had been at her dad's house in another state for the past month. That's when I really started noticing her phone behavior. When a specific notification sound played, just two quick beeps, her entire body would go rigid. Then she'd immediately delete whatever she'd seen. Something was very, very wrong with my daughter. I waited until she left for her sleep over that Saturday night. Then I did something I'd sworn I'd never do. I followed her. She didn't walk like a teenager heading To a fun sleepover. She walked like someone heading to their execution, taking a weird winding route through the neighborhood, doubling back twice, constantly checking over her shoulder. At one point, she stopped completely, stood under a street light, and I watched her take deep, shuddering breaths like she was preparing for battle. She pulled out her phone and typed something. Even from my car, I could see her hands shaking as she hit send. The response must have been immediate because her shoulders slumped into defeat. Then she kept walking. What I discovered made my stomach drop to the floor. She didn't go.

voice_to_text: Did sneaking out go way too far? My brother and I used to sneak out all the time, not for anything wild, just dumb, harmless stuff. Late night 7, 11 runs, laying on the trampoline to watch for meteors. One time we snuck out just to see if the new Taco Bell was open 24 hours. We weren't rebels, just bored kids who liked feeling like we were getting away with something. It started when I was 11 and he was 14. He'd tap three times on my wall around midnight, our signal. I tiptoe past our parents room in my socks, meet him by the laundry door and we'd sneak out like little burglars in pajamas. He always carried a backpack with snacks, flashlights and a notebook he pretended was mission logs. I think he just liked pretending we were spies. It became our tradition. Even when we weren't talking much during the day, we'd still sneak out. One time I fell asleep and missed the signal. The next morning, he left a granola bar and a sticky note in my sock drawer that said, rookie Mistake, you're on thin ice, Agent B. But as we got older, things changed, got busier with school, started driving, started dating. I assumed we just outgrown it. No more nightly missions, no more late Taco Bell disappointments. I tap on the wall sometimes just to see, but he never knocked back. Then one night, about a year after our last mission, I couldn't sleep. Too much energy. I tapped on the wall knowing it was pointless, but out of habit, I crept to the laundry room anyway and the back door was already open. I stepped outside. It was cold. Damn. The kind of quiet where even your own footsteps a little too loud. I walked to the side gate and that's when I saw him sitting in the driveway, hoodie up, facing away from me. His backpack. The backpack was next to him. I almost called out, but something about the way he was sitting stopped popped me. Shoulders hunched, arms on his knees like he was holding something back. I moved closer and heard it. Quiet, shaky breathing, then a sniff. He was crying. I crouched down beside the car, not sure if I should say anything, but then I heard him mumble something under his breath. I can't do it anymore. Or how she needed exactly eight minutes of silence when she got home from work before she could handle talking. I wrote down that she liked her apartment at exactly 72 degrees, not 71 or 73. That she always ordered extra pickles but never ate them. That she got cranky. I knew she was stressed when she started reorganizing her bookshelf, so I'd order her favorite Thai food before she even realized she was hungry. When she was upset, she'd clean the bathroom obsessively, so I'd run her a bath afterward. None of this felt calculated or weird to me. It just seemed like paying attention. But I never told her about it because it sounded super intense when I thought about explaining it. Like, hey, hey, babe, I've been documenting your behavior patterns for three years. voice_to_text: When did you realize some people have zero empathy? I found out when my new neighbor declared war on my sick daughter's magical night garden. My 7 year old daughter Lily has a rare skin condition. To put it simply, the sun hurts her. She can only play outside in the deep twilight just as the last bits of sun disappear. Because of this, her world was mostly indoors. To give her a little piece of magic that was just hers, we built a special garden in our backyard. It was a moon garden filled with flowers like moonflowers and evening primroses that only bloomed at night. We strung up soft twinkling fairy lights and for an hour or so each evening, Lily could be a normal kid in her enchanted space. It was the one thing that brought her pure joy. Then Mister Henderson moved in next door. At first he seemed fine, just a quiet, grumpy looking man. About a week after he moved in, he installed a security light on the side of his garage. But this wasn't a normal light. Normal. It was a commercial grade stadium style floodlight, a miniature sun. When he turned it on that first night, it blasted our entire backyard with harsh blue white light, completely washing out the fairy lights and bleaching the grass. I walked over the next day and knocked on his door. I explained very politely about Lily's condition and her special garden. I asked if he Might consider angling the light downwards so it only covered his property. He just stared at me. It's for my security, he said flatly. I need to see my whole property line. I tried again, my voice gentle. I understand, but it's just so bright. It's ruining my daughter's only safe place to play. He actually scoffed. Not my problem. Your kid needs to toughen up. The world's a bright place. He closed the door in my face. The effect was immediate and devastating. The harsh light never turned off. Running from dusk until dawn, Lily's moonflowers, which needed darkness to open, state tightly shut, then began to wilt. She would just stand at her window, tears in her eyes, watching her magical garden die. The light was so powerful, it even cut through her blackout curtains, making it hard for her to sleep. My heart broke every single night. I tried everything. I called the city, hoping to file a nuisance complaint. They sent an officer out who measured the light. Mr Henderson had done his research. The light was exactly one lumen under the legal limit to be considered a violation.

voice_to_text: This is the weirdest village I've ever seen. Because there is absolutely no red stuff allowed here. Even a small red flower that has just grown. It must be pinched off immediately and then buried in the soil and cleaned up. Otherwise it would attract that terrible monster. It turns out that in this isolated village, a terrible legend has been passed down. The legend says that deep in the forest, there lives a horrible group of monsters. They love the color red, but they hate yellow. Whenever something red appears in the village, they would kill all the villagers. So the mayor and the elders made a pact with the monsters. Nothing red could appear in the village. No one from the village was allowed to go outside. Every year, at the beginning of the year, raw meat was cut and thrown into the woods. For all this time, everyone kept the pact. And for many years, the village was quiet. And soon that piece was broken by a fool. He was holding a red fruit that was unique to the deep forest. That very night, the villagers on night watch noticed a red monster had slipped into the village. He rang the alarm bell to warn everyone that the creature was coming. Hearing the bell, the villagers ran to their homes. As a precaution, each family had built a cellar under their house. Nick, who was returning home, all the unaccompanied children, he took them back to their Homes and helped the other villagers to close the windows and doors. But he was too late to run. He was almost discovered by the monster. Meanwhile, Anna was waiting anxiously for Nick, as she is blind. So she had to raise her hand to try and get Nick to see. Instead of Nick, the monster was waiting for her. The monster was about to pounce on Anna. In the nick of time, Nick arrived just in time. He took Anna into the basement and hid. Everyone huddled together and looked to the floor, praying that the monster would leave sooner rather than later. And so it was. The group hid underground for the rest of the night. The next morning, monster was finally gone, but the doors of every house were marked with red marks. It was clear there was a good chance that the monster would return. The village chief hurriedly LED the men to throw a chunk of raw meat into the woods, asking for reconciliation with the monster. But by nightfall, something terrible happened again.
